*Mr Shi is leaving for the market in the early afternoon.*

**Mrs Shi**
Take the cassette to the market and the chair to the pastor.
(Finnish: Tuo lipas torille ja tuoli pastorille.)

**Narration**
Lion-Eating Poet in the Stone Room.
Mr. Shi, the poet from a stone room, likes to eat lions. He promises solemnly, that he will eat ten lions. Regularly he goes to the market to look at the lions. ...
(Chinese, Mandarin: 施氏食獅史
石室詩士施氏，嗜獅，誓食十獅。
氏時時適市視獅。
十時，適十獅適市。
是時，適施氏適市。
氏視是十獅，恃矢勢，使是十獅逝世。
氏拾是十獅屍，適石室。
石室濕，氏使侍拭石室。
石室拭，氏始試食是十獅。
食時，始識是十獅，實十石獅屍。
試釋是事。)

*Mr Shi runs into a group of his friends and is excited to see them.*

**Mr Shi** [Greetings]

**Someone from the group**: Can you tell me where you are going?
(Italian: Me diì 'ndù nd'é?)

**Mr Shi** Regularly I go to the market to look at the lions. ...

**Someone from the group** [Something like "We just came from there! We have never been to this market. It's really wonderful!"]

**Mr Shi** Tell me about your purchases!

**Someone from the group** What purchases?

**Mr Shi** About purchases, purchases, your little purchases!
(Russian: Раскажи мне про покупки!
Про какие про покупки?
Про покупки, про покупки, про покупочки твои!)

**Person A from the group** I went to the store and saw a huge potato, went home and was happy.
(Kikuyu: Dathie donyo daria duma dugu dakena dainoka!)

**Person G** On the butcher's shop sign the space between "Cheese" and "and" and "and" and "Sausage" was to small.
(German: Auf des Fleischhauers Schild war der Abstand zwischen "Käse" und "und" und "und" und "Wurst" zu klein geraten.)

**Person H** Between "or" and "and" and "and" and "and" and "and" and "or" there is always a space.
(German: Zwischen "oder" und "und" und "und" und "und" und "und" und "oder" ist immer ein Leerzeichen.)


 - Friend, buy me coconut. - Friend, I don't buy coconut, because I don't eat much coconut therefor I don't buy much coconut.
(Spanish: - Compadre, cómpreme un coco. - Compadre, no compro coco, porque poco coco como poco coco compro.)

 Who buys the expensive "paca", will pay for the expensive "paca". "Paca" is a little mammal from South America.
(Portuguese: Quem a paca cara compra, paca cara pagará.)

 Mail carriages you can buy in a shop that sells mail carriages.
(Dutch: Koetspoets koop je in de postkoetskoetspoetswinkel)

 The chubby woman Ba sells rice cake on the sea shore.
(Vietnamese: Bà ba béo bán bánh bèo bên bờ biển.)



 Brother of the brown gown, don't buy anymore brown gown, because who buy many brown gowns, pays for many brown gowns. I who bought many brown gowns, paid for many brwon gowns.
(Spanish: Compadre de la capa parda, no compre usted mas capa parda, que el que mucha capa parda compra, mucha capa parda paga. Yo que mucha capa parda compré, mucha capa parda pagué.)



 There was once a girl called Barbara.  Barbara had a greengrocery, and she sold rhubarb. Therefore everyone called her Rhubarb Barbara.  Later on she opened a cafe with a bar. It was written on the window: Rhubarb Barbara's Bar. Some wild men, real barbarians, came to visit: the Rhubarb Barbara's Bar Barbarians. Oh, what long beards those men had! They called the beards Rhubarb Barbara's Bar Barbarians' Beards. And the barber who had to trim the beards was the Rhubarb Barbara's Bar Barbarians' Beard
Barber!
(Dutch: Er was eens een meisje, dat heette Barbara. Barbara had een groentenwinkel en verkocht rabarber. Daarom noemden alle mensen dat meisje: Rabarberbarbara. Later begon Barbara een cafe met een bar. Op het raam stond: Rabarberbarbarabar. Daar kwamen wilde mannen op bezoek, echte barbaren: de Rabarberbarbarabarbarbaren. O, wat hadden die mannen lange baarden! Die baarden noemden ze: Rabarberbarbarabarbarbarenbaarden. En de barbier die die lange baarden moest knippen was de: Rabarberbarbarabarbarbarenbaardenbarbier!)






*Mr Shi goes to the pastor*

**Mr Shi** The chair's leg got undone (broken)
(Greek, Modern: Της καρέκλας το ποδάρι ξεκαρεκλοποδαρώθηκε.)


Pedro Pablo Pérez Pereira, poor portuguese painter paints pictures for little money to survive in Paris.
(Spanish: Pedro Pablo Pérez Pereira, poor portuguese painter paints pictures for little money to survive in Paris.)

Not true! Paulo Pereira Pinto Peixoto, poor Portuguese painter paints perfectily doors, walls and washbasins for little money, boss!

